    <h1 class="big-heading">Drug Withdrawal</h1>

    <p>


        Withdrawal is a complex process that occurs when a dependent person suddenly stops or reduces drug use. This can
        cause the body to adapt to the absence of the substance, leading to a range of physical & emotional symptoms
        that can be mild to severe. Common withdrawal symptoms can include anxiety, depression, insomnia, muscle aches,
        sweating, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea & more.

        <br><br>

        The causes of withdrawal can be multifactorial, including genetics, environment & mental health conditions
        that contribute to addiction & dependence. Addressing these underlying issues is critical for long-term
        recovery.

    </p>

    <img src="imgs/withdrawal.webp" alt="withdrawal" class="img">

    <p>

        The severity & duration of withdrawal symptoms depend on various factors, including the type of drug used, the
        dosage, the duration of use & individual factors such as genetics, age & health status. Specific
        withdrawal timelines can vary for different drugs & people may experience protracted withdrawal symptoms that
        can last for months to years after stopping substance abuse.

        <br><br>

        Withdrawal symptoms are associated with the abuse of various drugs, including benzodiazepine medication,
        barbiturates, opioids & marijuana. Specific opioids, such as fentanyl, present an increased risk of
        unintentional overdose due to lowered tolerance. Benzodiazepines can be dangerous when combined with opioids or
        other central nervous system depressants such as alcohol. Stimulant abuse often involves binges & crashes,
        with withdrawal symptoms that include depression, irritability, fatigue & cravings.
    </p>

    <img src="imgs/withdrawal-2.webp" alt="withdrawal" class="img">

    <p>

        Treatment for withdrawal involves medical & behavioral therapies, including medications & counseling. In
        severe cases, detoxification or inpatient treatment may be necessary. It is crucial to explore treatment options
        with loved ones & healthcare providers, as withdrawal from certain drugs can be fatal if not medically
        managed. Abruptly stopping medication or drug use without proper medical supervision can be harmful & it is
        essential to consult a doctor before reducing or stopping drug use.

        <br><br>

        Coping with withdrawal involves seeking help, maintaining a healthy lifestyle & stress management. Follow-up
        care is critical for many individuals, including ongoing support, counseling, medication-assisted treatment, and
        other forms of therapy, to maintain sobriety & address the underlying issues that led to substance abuse.

    </p>

    <img src="imgs/withdrawal-3.webp" alt="withdrawal" class="img">

    <p>

        It is important to note that treating withdrawal is not the same as treating dependence or addiction. Patients
        require medical supervision & therapy to manage the physical & emotional symptoms of drug withdrawal, as
        well as addressing the underlying issues that led to substance abuse in the first place.

    </p>

